This technique also showed that the amount of the melanin pigment of the eyespot cup from larger specimens was lower than that of the smallest ones. However, this character is of little use in field identification or in routine evaluation of preserved animals. The eyespots cannot be easily observed most likely due to the following reasons: 
1
) in large animals the cuticle becomes thickened and the amount of melanin of the eyespot cap is lower than in smaller ones, hindering their observation, remaining invisible without using the confocal technique; 
2
) in preserved specimens of all sizes, the cuticle of the worm has often lifted off and the eyespot has become internalised.
